This paper discusses the development of a framework for designing and evaluating digital health interventions, which involves the integration of behavioral theories, behavior change techniques, and persuasive system design principles. This work is highly relevant to the field of human-computer interaction (cs.HC), as it focuses on the design and evaluation of interactive systems for health behavior change. Additionally, the paper touches on topics related to cybernetics (cs.CY), computer engineering (cs.CE), social and information networks (cs.SI), and computational linguistics (cs.CL), as it discusses the use of taxonomies and workflows for organizing and analyzing data in digital health interventions.
